\section[sec:parameters]{Command parameters}

The typical simple command in \caps{LaTeX} has one or two primary parameters enclosed
between curly brackets.  In addition, many commands (both simple and environment) accept
also optional parameters that specify an ordering, a label, or any extra information.
When present, optional parameters may be specified in any order, as long as they
precede any of the primary parameters.  Moreover, each class of optional parameter is
distinguished by the set of characters used for delimitation.  Ordering parameters
are enclosed in curved brackets, labelling parameters in square brackets, and extra
parameters between angle brackets.

Note that not all optional parameters are meaningful for all existing commands.
Some commands may, for instance, accept only an order and/or a label parameter,
while others accept only extra parameters.  In fact, no command exists that accepts
all three classes of optional parameters, and there are several which accept none.
\sref{tab:permlist} lists the classes accepted for each of all existing commands,
both simple and environment ones.  An exact definition of the terms used is shown
in \sref{tab:permdesc}.


