\section[sec:order]{Notes on ordering in the context of sub-pages}

This section applies to those blocks that have an associated ordering, namely wrapper
blocks, sectional blocks, and the custom blocks (boxouts and theorems).  Recall that a
wrapper is essentially a floater element with a caption and an order associated with it.
There are four elements in \lambtex that fit into this category: equations, printouts,
tables, and figures.  As for sectional blocks, these are the ones that produce parts,
sections, sub-sections, and sub-sub-sections.  There are some special --- though as
you shall see based on common sense --- rules that must be followed concerning the
order parameter and the hyperlinking of blocks with associated ordering, particularly
in the context of sub-pages.  The rules are as follows:

\begin{enumerate}

\item
	Only numbered elements may be referred to using \code{\\ref} and \code{\\sref}
	commands:

	\p<!indent>{Unless the user explicitly demanded an empty ordering, sectional
	commands have by default a number.  As for wrappers, they always have an
	associated order.  In the case of custom environments, the situation varies.}

	It makes sense that the hyperlinking commands that are supposed to produce a
	number should only be used with wrappers, numbered sectional blocks, or numbered
	custom environments.  These commands are \code{\\ref} and \code{\\sref}.
	On the other hand, because \code{\\mref} does not output a number, it is
	always allowed.

\item
	You must explicitly provide a manual ordering for sub-paged wrappers, sectional
	blocks, or custom blocks:

	\p<!indent>{A sub-paged element is one that is declared inside a \code{subpage}
	block (see \sref{sec:subpage}).  Because they lie outside the main flow of the
	document, these elements are not automatically numbered.  You must therefore
	explicitly provide them with an ordering parameter.  This is done by inserting
	the numbering between parentheses.  Note that in the case of sectional commands
	or custom blocks an empty ordering is allowed.}

\item
	You may not provide a manual ordering for wrappers, sectional blocks, or custom
	blocks defined outside a sub-page:

	\p<!indent>{This rule is complementary to the previous one.  Because these
	blocks are numbered automatically by \lambtex when present in the main document,
	you may not interfere with that automatism by providing an explicit ordering.
	Note, however, that an empty ordering is always allowed for sectional commands
	or custom blocks.}

\end{enumerate}

\section[sec:extra]{Extra parameters}

Remember that extra parameters are those enclosed between angle brackets, and always
precede any mandatory parameters the command may have.  Canonically, specifying that a
parameter \code{alpha} should have a value \code{x} is done by declaring \code{alpha=x}
as the extra parameter.  Should the command accept multiple parameters, these can
be separated by inserting a '\code{,}' (comma) between them.  \sref{tab:extradesc}
below lists all the existing extra parameters together with the accepted values for each.

\begin[tab:extradesc]{table}
{List of all existing extra parameters and associated range of values.
Consult \sref{tab:permlist} for a list of which of these parameters are
accepted for each command.}
\begin{tabular}{rl}
\head
| Parameter		| Accepted values |
\body
| \code{initial}	| Boolean |
| \code{indent}		| Boolean or \code{auto} |
| \code{box}		| Boolean |
| \code{nums}		| Boolean |
| \code{zebra}		| Boolean |
| \code{mult}		| Integer between 0 and 9 (inclusive) |
| \code{frame}		| Boolean |
| \code{width}		| Integer between 1 and 100 (inclusive), or \code{auto} |
| \code{bul}		| Discrete values: \code{disc}, \code{circle}, \code{square}, \code{none} |
| \code{num}		| Discrete values:
			\code{0}, \code{i}, \code{I}, \code{a}, \code{A},
			\code{decimal}, \code{lower-roman}, \code{upper-roman},
			\code{lower-alpha}, \code{upper-alpha}, \code{none} |
